## MVP Scope

The first working version should focus on the smallest set of features that prove the concept.

### MVP Features

* Installable PWA shell
* Daily check-in form
* Reminder creation and completion
* Local notes storage
* Local hydration log
* Companion chat UI
* Offline fallback behavior
* Optional Grok integration through secure relay
* Large text and high contrast support

### Out of Scope for MVP

* Full family dashboard
* Advanced analytics
* Multi-user cloud sync
* Complex medical workflows
* Emergency alerting system
* Full voice transcription pipeline beyond simple browser support

## Success Criteria

NPC MVP is successful if:

* A senior can open it and understand the home screen without training
* The app works offline for notes, reminders, and logs
* Text is easy to read and controls are easy to tap
* The user can complete a daily check-in in under one minute
* The app can deliver a calm, helpful companion experience
* Privacy settings are understandable and trustworthy

## Future Expansion Ideas

* Family sync dashboard with consent controls
* Exportable health and mood summaries
* Caregiver alerts for missed check-ins
* Routine learning and adaptive reminder timing
* Smarter local-only sentiment support
* Calendar integration
* Guided wellness routines
* Larger tablet-first layout

## Development Notes

This project should be built with the simplest reliable path first. Accessibility, clarity, and stability matter more than flashy features. The companion must feel trustworthy, gentle, and easy to use.

---

# What Needs To Be Done

## Phase 1: Planning and Validation

* Finalize MVP feature list
* Confirm whether pyTincture is the right UI framework for accessibility and browser support
* Decide how much voice support is required for MVP
* Confirm local-only data model
* Decide what AI tasks are allowed online
* Define privacy and consent wording

## Phase 2: Base Project Setup

* Create project folder structure
* Build the HTML shell for the PWA
* Add manifest.json and installable app metadata
* Add service worker for offline caching
* Load Pyodide successfully in browser
* Confirm Python package loading strategy with micropip

## Phase 3: Local Storage Foundation

* Integrate IndexedDB storage layer
* Connect DuckDB-WASM for structured local queries
* Define database schema for reminders, notes, hydration logs, mood check-ins, and settings
* Add local backup/export strategy
* Add encryption helper for sensitive data

## Phase 4: Core UI Development

* Build Today screen
* Build Check-In screen
* Build Reminders screen
* Build Notes screen
* Build Companion Chat screen
* Build Settings screen
* Add large text mode and high contrast mode
* Add large-button mobile layout testing

## Phase 5: Reminder and Routine Engine

* Create reminder creation/edit flow
* Add repeat schedules
* Add done and snooze actions
* Add hydration tracking
* Add medication tracking flags
* Add daily prompt scheduling
* Add read-aloud reminder support

## Phase 6: Companion Logic

* Create offline fallback response rules
* Build local prompt templates for empathy and routine support
* Add local conversation history storage
* Add daily greeting logic
* Add mood-based prompt suggestions

## Phase 7: Online AI Integration

* Build secure relay for Grok API requests
* Add anonymization/redaction layer before sending text
* Add consent check before online calls
* Add online/offline indicator in UI
* Add graceful fallback when API is unavailable

## Phase 8: Voice and Accessibility

* Add speech synthesis read-back
* Add browser voice input support where available
* Add clear non-voice fallback paths
* Test large font and contrast modes
* Test tap target sizes and screen readability
* Simplify navigation labels for senior users

## Phase 9: Security and Privacy

* Add HTTPS-only deployment
* Configure CSP headers
* Add secure handling of API keys on backend relay
* Add local PIN protection if desired
* Encrypt sensitive stored data
* Add consent screens and privacy explanations

## Phase 10: Testing

* Test on Android browsers
* Test on iPhone Safari PWA install flow
* Test offline behavior fully
* Test older devices for performance
* Test reminder reliability after reload/reopen
* Test with real users for readability and ease of use

## Phase 11: Launch Preparation

* Write onboarding copy
* Write privacy policy and consent language
* Create icon set and polished branding
* Prepare deployment hosting
* Verify installability and caching
* Document setup and maintenance

## Priority Order

1. Define MVP clearly
2. Get PWA shell running
3. Set up local storage
4. Build Today, Check-In, Reminders, Notes
5. Add offline companion logic
6. Add accessibility improvements
7. Add Grok relay integration
8. Test on phones and tablets
9. Polish and launch

## Biggest Risks to Solve Early

* pyTincture compatibility and accessibility fit
* Browser voice input limitations
* PWA notification/reminder behavior on mobile
* Secure AI integration without exposing API keys
* Making the UI simple enough for real senior adoption

## Recommended Immediate Next Steps

* Write the final MVP feature list
* Build the base PWA shell
* Test Pyodide loading in browser
* Build one working Today screen
* Add one reminder flow and one daily check-in flow
* Validate the UI with large-font mobile testing
